      "West Palm Beach's historic streets — El Cid, SoSo, Flamingo Park, Prospect Park — are full of Spanish and Mediterranean homes, and many of the paver walkways and driveways here have been in place for years. Time shows: the warm color has faded, mold builds up in the shade of mature trees, and the joint sand has washed out so weeds come through. A clean and reseal restores that period look without disturbing the character of the home.",
      'We deep-clean the pavers to lift the mold, weeds and grime, then re-sand the joints with polymeric sand that hardens to hold weeds and ants out. The sealer is where the character comes back — a wet-look enhancer deepens the warm clay tones that suit these 1920s to 40s homes, or a matte seal keeps the softer, aged finish if that reads more true to the house.',
      'There is no HOA to answer to on these streets, and cleaning and sealing the existing pavers does not change the design, so it stays in step with any historic district it falls in. It is a low-disruption way to keep a character-rich in-town home looking cared for, protecting the finish against the sun between visits.',
    ],
    localNote: 'Mature trees shade these older in-town lots, so mold builds up in the joints and on the surface — a deep clean lifts it, and a warm-toned seal keeps the finish true to the period architecture.',
    faqs: [
      { q: 'Will a wet-look seal suit my historic El Cid or Flamingo Park home?', a: 'It often does. A wet-look enhancer deepens the warm clay and earth tones that read true to 1920s–40s architecture, without changing the pavers themselves. If you prefer the softer aged look, a matte seal keeps that — we show you both on your own pavers.' },
      { q: 'Mold keeps coming back under my trees — will sealing help?', a: 'The deep clean strips the existing mold, and the sealer makes the surface easier to rinse and slower to grow it back. In the shade of mature trees mold returns eventually, so a reseal every few years keeps ahead of it.' },
      { q: 'Do I need any approval to clean and seal pavers in a historic district?', a: 'Cleaning and sealing existing pavers does not change the design, so it typically stays in step with a historic district without a submittal. There is no HOA on these streets, which keeps it simple.' },
