  'delray-beach': {
    lede: 'Around Lake Ida and the beach the salt air and heavy summer rain leave mold on the pavers and wash the joint sand out — a deep clean and reseal takes it all back to new.',
    intro: [
      "Delray's east side — Lake Ida, the beach district, Del-Ida Park — sits close to the water, and the pavers there take the brunt of it. Salt air and heavy summer rain leave black mold on the surface, fade the color and wash the sand out of the joints so weeds and ants move in. On these established coastal homes the base is usually still sound, so a clean and reseal restores the pavers without a rebuild.",
      'We deep-clean the surface to pull off the mold, weeds and salt-borne grime, then re-sand the joints with polymeric sand that hardens to lock weeds and ants out. Then we seal — matte to keep the natural coastal look, or a wet-look enhancer to deepen the color — and that seal is what does the heavy lifting this close to the ocean.',
      'The sealer shields the color against the salt and the strong sun, and it makes the surface bead off the summer downpours and rinse clean instead of staining. On a beach-district lot it is the difference between pavers that gray out in a season and pavers that hold their finish for years on a simple reseal cycle.',
    ],
    localNote: 'Coastal east-side Delray lots deal with constant salt and heavy summer rain, so mold and joint weeds return fast — sealing on a maintenance cycle keeps the color protected and the surface easy to rinse clean.',
