  'boynton-beach': {
    lede: 'Along the Intracoastal and Boynton\'s eastern streets the salt and damp air grow mold on the pavers and wash the joint sand out — a deep clean and reseal restores them without a teardown.',
    intro: [
      "Boynton Beach's best paver work is on the water and to the east — the Intracoastal waterfront, Harbor Estates, Chapel Hill, Lake Eden. Near the water the salt and the damp air are hard on pavers: mold builds up in the shade, the color fades and the joint sand washes out so weeds and ants take hold. Where the base under these 1960s to 90s installs is still sound, a clean and reseal brings the pavers back without a rebuild.",
      'We deep-clean the surface to strip the mold, weeds and grime, then re-sand the joints with polymeric sand that hardens to keep weeds and ants out. The sealer finishes it — matte for the natural look, or a wet-look enhancer to deepen the color — and it is what protects the pavers against the salt-heavy air near the Intracoastal.',
      'The seal also helps the surface shed the heavy summer rain instead of holding it, which matters on the damp ground near the water. It keeps the color from fading, makes the pavers easier to rinse clean, and holds off the mold so a waterfront driveway or pool deck stays looking maintained between visits.',
    ],
    localNote: 'Waterfront Boynton lots near the Intracoastal sit in damp, salt-heavy air, so mold and joint weeds come back quickly — a reseal on a maintenance cycle keeps the color protected and the surface easy to clean.',
    faqs: [
      { q: 'My Boynton home backs onto the Intracoastal — how often should I reseal?', a: 'This close to the water, every two to three years. The salt air and humidity wear a sealer faster near the Intracoastal, and resealing on that cycle keeps the color protected and slows the mold from returning.' },
      { q: 'The damp air near the water grows mold on my pavers — will sealing stop it?', a: 'The deep clean strips the mold off, and the sealer makes the surface easier to rinse and slower to grow it back. Near the water it returns over time, so a reseal every couple of years is what keeps ahead of it.' },
      { q: 'Weeds and ants are coming up through my joints — what fixes that?', a: 'We refill the joints with polymeric sand that hardens into a firm bond, which locks out the weeds and ants that had moved into the washed-out sand. It is the most reliable way to keep the joints clean on a waterfront lot.' },
